Key Characteristics

  • Summer capital of J&K but "highly backward" health infrastructure. Major hospitals present but primary healthcare gaps
  • Major hospitals present but primary healthcare gaps
  • HIGHEST respiratory burden with clinical evidence (48%, RSV 46.1% of SARI). Extended seasonal crisis (1.8x winter, Oct-Mar extended season)
  • Srinagar demonstrates the most severe combination of low literacy + healthcare backwardness + extreme respiratory burden among all capitals analyzed
    •

    *Synthetic Data Considerations

    • Population: ~1.78M (metro 2025); literacy 69.41%; predominantly Muslim population; sex ratio varies by area
    • Respiratory Disease: Very high burden—RSV most common (46.1% of SARI cases); lung cancer rates 19.34 per 100,000 (males in Srinagar); influenza A/H1N1 and seasonal flu cocirculation; climate change increasing respiratory illness burden
    • Healthcare: Major hospitals include Bone & Joint Hospital Barzulla, Children's Hospital Bemina (500 beds); Srinagar classified as "highly backward" in health infrastructure development; significant primary healthcare gaps despite being capital
    • Seasonal Patterns: Strong winter peaks (Oct-Mar) for respiratory infections; RSV peaks during study periods; influenza cocirculation in winter months
    • Socioeconomic: Summer capital of J&K; per capita income ₹18,717 (2003-04 data); significant slum population (2,016 people across 7 clusters); high urban density; tourism-dependent economy
